  "description": "Lewis MacKenzie was born in Truro, Nova Scotia a long time ago. He is a graduate of Xavier Junior College of Sydney Nova Scotia and the University of Manitoba. During his thirty six year military career he served nine years in Germany with NATO forces and managed to avoid service in Ottawa by fitting in nine peacekeeping tours of duty in the Gaza Strip, Cyprus, Cairo, Vietnam, Central America and Sarajevo. In 1990 Lewis was appointed commander of the United [&#8230;]",
  "content:encoded": "<p>Lewis MacKenzie was born in <a title=\"The Town of Truro\" href=\"http://www.truro.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Truro</a>, <a title=\"The Province of Nova Scotia\" href=\"http://novascotia.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Nova Scotia</a> a long time ago. He is a graduate of <a title=\"Xavier Junior College\" href=\"http://xaviers.edu/main/\" target=\"_blank\">Xavier Junior College</a> of <a title=\"Sydney\" href=\"http://sydney.capebretonisland.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Sydney</a> Nova Scotia and the <a title=\"University of Manitoba\" href=\"http://umanitoba.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">University of Manitoba</a>. During his thirty six year military career he served nine years in Germany with <a title=\"NATO\" href=\"http://www.nato.int\" target=\"_blank\">NATO</a> forces and managed to avoid service in <a title=\"City of Ottawa\" href=\"http://ottawa.ca/en\" target=\"_blank\">Ottawa</a> by fitting in nine peacekeeping tours of duty in the <a title=\"Op Danaca\" href=\"http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/operations-abroad-past/op-danaca.page\" target=\"_blank\">Gaza Strip</a>, <a title=\"Op Snowgoose\" href=\"http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/operations-abroad-current/op-snowgoose.pagehttp://\" target=\"_blank\">Cyprus</a>, <a title=\"UN in Egypt\" href=\"http://www.un.org.eg/index.aspx?pageid=33\" target=\"_blank\">Cairo</a>, Vietnam, Central America and <a title=\"Op Harmony\" href=\"http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/operations-abroad-past/op-harmony.page\" target=\"_blank\">Sarajevo.</a></p>\n<p>In 1990 Lewis was appointed commander of the <a title=\"UNITED NATIONS OBSERVER GROUP IN CENTRAL AMERICA \" href=\"http://www.un.org/en/peacekeeping/missions/past/onuca.htm\" target=\"_blank\">United Nation’s Observer mission in Central America</a>. Two years later he was assigned to the United Nation’s Protection Force in Yugoslavia. In May of that year he created and assumed command of Sector Sarajevo and with a small contingent of soldiers from 31 countries opened the Sarajevo airport for the delivery of humanitarian aid during the height of the Bosnian civil war. As a result he became the first Canadian, military or civilian to be awarded a second <a title=\"The Meritorious Service Cross\" href=\"http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=15209&lan=eng\" target=\"_blank\">Meritorious Service Cross</a>.</p>\n<p>Since his retirement from the military, Lew has been under contract to <a title=\"CBS\" href=\"http://www.cbs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">CBS</a> and <a title=\"CTV\" href=\"http://www.ctv.ca\" target=\"_blank\">CTV</a> and frequently appears on many of the international TV and radio networks as a commentator on international affairs. He is a regular contributor to the <a title=\"The Globe and Mail\" href=\"http://www.globeandmail.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Globe and Mail</a> and is in demand as a lecturer on the subject of leadership.</p>\n<p>Lew is still active in motor racing having won national and provincial titles in sports car and formula car racing commencing in 1979. He is the 2010 <a title=\"Province of Québec\" href=\"http://www.bonjourquebec.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Quebec</a> – <a title=\"Province of Ontario\" href=\"http://www.ontario.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Ontario</a> interprovincial champion in formula ford racing and defended his title in 2011. He continues to race competively in his 74th year. A documentary, &#8220;General Racing&#8221;, was released in 2014.</p>\n<p>Lew was made an Honourary Chief of the <a title=\"Toronto Police Service\" href=\"http://www.torontopolice.on.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Metro Toronto Police Force</a> in 1993. He holds Honourary Doctorates from numerous Canadian Universities, is a member of the Board of Advisors of the <a title=\"Canadian Federation of AIDS Research\" href=\"http://www.cahr-acrv.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian Federation of AIDS Research</a> and sits on a number of corporate boards with international interests. Following the attacks of 11 September 2001 General MacKenzie was appointed one of two advisors to the <a title=\"Premier of Ontario\" href=\"http://www.premier.gov.on.ca/en/bio\" target=\"_blank\">Premier of Ontario</a> on counter-terrorism and emergency measures.</p>\n<p>In 2002 and 2006 respectively Lew was invested with the <a title=\"Order of Ontario\" href=\"http://www.citizenship.gov.on.ca/english/citizenship/honours/orderofontario.shtml\" target=\"_blank\">Order of Ontario</a> and the <a title=\"Order of Canada\" href=\"http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=14940&lan=eng\" target=\"_blank\">Order of Canada</a> for his humanitarian work in Africa.</p>\n<p>In spite of the above, Dora MacKinnon of Baysville, Ontario is still married to the General. Their daughter Kimm works, rides, races formula cars with her father&#8217;s team and resides in Ottawa.</p>\n<p>For ore information about the <a title=\"The Never Forgotten National Memorial \" href=\"http://www.nfnm.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Never Forgotten National Memorial</a> project, please visit  www.nfnm.ca</p>\n<p>Follow me on Twitter @MikeLacroix32</p>\n<p class=\"wpview-selection-before\">You can support this site by shopping on <a title=\"Amazon.ca\" href=\"http://www.amazon.ca?_encoding=UTF8&tag=thecanamilihi-20\" target=\"_blank\">Amazon</a>.  You still enjoy Amazon&#8217;s great prices, but a portion of your purchase goes to supporting the show.</p>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-789-23\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/CMHP-Episode-036-MGen-Lewis-MacKenzie.mp3?_=23\" /><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/CMHP-Episode-036-MGen-Lewis-MacKenzie.mp3\">http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/CMHP-Episode-036-MGen-Lewis-MacKenzie.mp3</a></audio>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/at-26-years...jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-791\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/at-26-years..-243x300.jpeg\" alt=\"at 26 years..\" width=\"243\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/at-26-years..-243x300.jpeg 243w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/at-26-years...jpeg 443w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 243px) 100vw, 243px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Lieutenant Lew MacKenzie of the Queen&#8217;s Own Rifles of Canada at 26 years old.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mac-Cyprus.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-792\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mac-Cyprus-216x300.jpeg\" alt=\"Mac-Cyprus\" width=\"216\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mac-Cyprus-216x300.jpeg 216w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mac-Cyprus.jpeg 379w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 216px) 100vw, 216px\" /></a></p>\n<p>LCol Lew MacKenzie Serves as the CO of 1PPCLI in Cyprus.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mitterrand-2-001.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-793\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mitterrand-2-001-300x262.jpeg\" alt=\"Mitterrand 2 001\" width=\"300\" height=\"262\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mitterrand-2-001-300x262.jpeg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Mitterrand-2-001.jpeg 508w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a>    <a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Visit-Pres-Mitterrand.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-794\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Visit-Pres-Mitterrand-300x179.jpeg\" alt=\"Visit Pres Mitterrand\" width=\"300\" height=\"179\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Visit-Pres-Mitterrand-300x179.jpeg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Visit-Pres-Mitterrand.jpeg 480w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>General MacKenzie briefs the President of France, François Mitterrand during an unexpected visit to the Former Yugoslavia.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Sarajevo-Airport.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-804\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Sarajevo-Airport-195x300.png\" alt=\"Sarajevo Airport\" width=\"195\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Sarajevo-Airport-195x300.png 195w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Sarajevo-Airport.png 405w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px\" /></a></p>\n<p>MGen MacKenzie takes control of the Sarajevo Airport.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Trudy-1.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-802\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Trudy-1-222x300.png\" alt=\"Trudy 1\" width=\"222\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Trudy-1-222x300.png 222w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Trudy-1.png 430w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 222px) 100vw, 222px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Honorary portrait of Lewis MacKenzie in the Canadian War Museum.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Colin-and-Lew.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-803\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Colin-and-Lew-300x272.png\" alt=\"Colin and Lew\" width=\"300\" height=\"272\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Colin-and-Lew-300x272.png 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Colin-and-Lew.png 499w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Lew visits with Colin Powell.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1297608084500_ORIGINAL.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-805\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1297608084500_ORIGINAL-300x201.jpg\" alt=\"1297608084500_ORIGINAL\" width=\"300\" height=\"201\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1297608084500_ORIGINAL-300x201.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1297608084500_ORIGINAL.jpg 650w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Lew&#8217;s other passion &#8211; Race cars!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
